docs.abstract: Apple, Microsoft and Google need more access to our data as they promote new phones and personal computers that are powered by artificial intelligence. Should we trust them?
docs.snippet: Apple, Microsoft and Google need more access to our data as they promote new phones and personal computers that are powered by artificial intelligence. Should we trust them?
docs.lead_paragraph: Apple, Microsoft and Google are heralding a new era of what they describe as artificially intelligent smartphones and computers. The devices, they say, will automate tasks like editing photos and wishing a friend a happy birthday.

headline.main: What the Arrival of A.I. Phones and Computers Means for Our Data
headline.print_headline: A.I. Devices Want More Of Our Data

docs.abstract: Brad Smith testified before a House committee a year after Chinese hackers infiltrated Microsoft’s technology and penetrated government networks.
docs.snippet: Brad Smith testified before a House committee a year after Chinese hackers infiltrated Microsoft’s technology and penetrated government networks.
docs.lead_paragraph: Republican lawmakers questioned a senior Microsoft executive on Thursday about the company’s presence in China, about a year after Chinese hackers used the tech giant’s systems to launch a devastating hack of federal government networks.

headline.main: Lawmakers Question Microsoft’s President About Its Presence in China
headline.print_headline: Lawmakers Question Microsoft Executive About Company’s Presence in China

docs.abstract: The leading companies are co-opting Silicon Valley’s traditional cycle of disruption.
docs.snippet: The leading companies are co-opting Silicon Valley’s traditional cycle of disruption.
docs.lead_paragraph: Silicon Valley prides itself on disruption: Start-ups develop new technologies, upend existing markets and overtake incumbents. This cycle of creative destruction brought us the personal computer, the internet and the smartphone. But in recent years, a handful of incumbent tech companies have sustained their dominance. Why? We believe they have learned how to co-opt potentially disruptive start-ups before they can become competitive threats.

headline.main: How Big Tech Is Killing Innovation

byline.original: By Mark Lemley and Matt Wansley

docs.abstract: The tech giant has been accused of stifling competition by packaging its video conferencing app with other tools like Word and Excel.
docs.snippet: The tech giant has been accused of stifling competition by packaging its video conferencing app with other tools like Word and Excel.
docs.lead_paragraph: European Union regulators on Tuesday charged Microsoft with breaking antitrust rules by bundling its Teams video conferencing and collaboration software with a suite of other productivity tools, giving it an unfair advantage over rivals.

headline.main: E.U. Charges Microsoft With Antitrust Violations Over Teams Bundling
headline.print_headline: Microsoft’s Bundling of Teams Is Antitrust Breach, E.U. Says

docs.abstract: Humane’s Ai Pin was supposed to free people from smartphones, but sales have been slow. Now Humane is talking to HP and others about a potential sale.

docs.lead_paragraph: Days before gadget reviewers weighed in on the Humane Ai Pin, a futuristic wearable device powered by artificial intelligence, the founders of the company gathered their employees and encouraged them to brace themselves. The reviews might be disappointing, they warned.

docs.abstract: “They really sort of make you feel like it’s Christmas and Coachella at the same time.”
docs.snippet: “They really sort of make you feel like it’s Christmas and Coachella at the same time.”
docs.lead_paragraph: This week we go to Cupertino, Calif., for Apple’s annual Worldwide Developers Conference and talk with Tripp Mickle, a New York Times reporter, about all of the new features Apple announced and the company’s giant leap into artificial intelligence. Then, we explore what was another tumultuous week for Elon Musk, who navigated a shareholders vote to re-approve his massive compensation package at Tesla, amid new claims that he had sex with subordinates at SpaceX. And finally — let’s play HatGPT.

headline.main: Apple Joins the A.I. Party, Elon’s Wild Week and HatGPT

docs.abstract: The Justice Department and the Federal Trade Commission agreed to divide responsibility for investigating three major players in the artificial intelligence industry.
docs.snippet: The Justice Department and the Federal Trade Commission agreed to divide responsibility for investigating three major players in the artificial intelligence industry.
docs.lead_paragraph: Federal regulators have reached a deal that allows them to proceed with antitrust investigations into the dominant roles that Microsoft, OpenAI and Nvidia play in the artificial intelligence industry, in the strongest sign of how regulatory scrutiny into the powerful technology has escalated.

headline.main: U.S. Clears Way for Antitrust Inquiries of Nvidia, Microsoft and OpenAI
headline.print_headline: A.I. Firms Face Scrutiny For Evidence Of Antitrust
